  "prompt": "How do you say thank you in Arabic? Does it depend on who you're speaking to?",
  "response": "In Arabic, \"thank you\" is typically expressed as \"\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0627\u064b\" (shukran). This form is generally used regardless of who you are speaking to. \n\nHowever, if you want to be more polite or formal, especially in certain contexts, you might say \"\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0627\u064b \u062c\u0632\u064a\u0644\u0627\u064b\" (shukran jazeelan), which means \"thank you very much,\" or \"\u0623\u0644\u0641 \u0634\u0643\u0631\" (alf shukr), meaning \"a thousand thanks.\"\n\nFor expressing gratitude towards someone older or in a more formal setting, you might use \"\u0623\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0643\" (ashkurak \u2013 to a male) or \"\u0623\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0643\u0650\" (ashkuraki \u2013 to a female), which translates to \"I thank you.\"\n\nWhile \"\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0627\u064b\" (shukran) is universally accepted for saying thank you, you may use the variations to suit the context and relationship dynamics.",
